*   **Why It Resonates:** It touches the core emotion of nationalism. Citizens feel their country is being "governed from abroad." This makes the Framework look like an invasion.

#### 2. The "Economic Suicide" Argument
*   **Target:** *Article 2.2 (Transition Justice) & 2.3 (True Cost Pricing)*
*   **The Argument:** "The Framework will crash the global economy and cause mass poverty."
*   **What They Say:**
    > *"Shifting to 'Regenerative Flourishing' requires destroying trillions of dollars in assets overnight. You cannot dissolve the fossil fuel industry without causing a recession. You cannot implement 'True Cost Pricing' without doubling the price of food and transport. This is a recipe for inflation, unemployment, and social unrest. The 'Transition Fund' is a fantasy; there is no money to pay for it without causing a debt crisis."*
*   **Why It Resonates:** It appeals to self-preservation. The average citizen cares more about the price of gas and groceries than the "Rights of Nature." If the Framework makes life expensive, it will be voted out.

#### 3. The "Green Neocolonialism" Argument
*   **Target:** *Article 1.3 (Rights of Nature) & 1.1 (Planetary Interdependence)*
*   **The Argument:** "The West is trying to keep the Global South poor."
*   **What They Say:**
    > *"The Global North destroyed its environment to get rich (1800-1900). Now, they want to use this 'Covenant' to prevent the rest of the world from developing. The '70% Rule' means we cannot build the infrastructure we need. The 'Carbon Caps' are a tariff on our survival. This is not about saving the planet; it is about maintaining the wealth gap. We will not accept a framework that locks us out of the industrial age."*
*   **Why It Resonates:** It is historically accurate. The Global South (India, Africa, Latin America) has the most to lose from restrictions on growth. If the Framework is seen as "Western Values imposed on Non-Western Nations," the UN consensus collapses.

